    "title": "Mourning and Mortality",
    "xlist": "",
    "yc_attrs": "",
    "ci_attrs": "",
    "description": "This course explores the relation between mourning and mortality in a number of seminal texts from the Western tradition. We begin by studying two of the most influential accounts of the relation to death: Plato's <i>Phaedo</i> and Epicurus's <i>Letter to Menoeceus,</i> with their further developments in Augustine's <i>Confessions</i> and Lucretius's <i>On the Nature of Things,</i> respectively. We then follow a trajectory that reaches from the Roman Stoics and Spinoza to Kierkegaard, Schopenhauer, Nietzsche, Freud, and Derrida. This sets the stage for addressing topics that haunt the entire tradition, including the conceptual definition of death, the psychological fear of death, the nature of care, the notion of loss, and the problem of mourning.",
